    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Man is like to vanity,.... Is vanity itself, in every age, state, and condition; yea, in his best estate, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 39:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; or, \"to the breath\" (h) of the mouth, as Kimchi; which is gone as soon as seen almost: or, to a vapour (i); to which the life of man is compared, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "James 4:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "his days are as a shadow that passeth away; as the former denotes the frailty and mortality of man, this the shortness of his duration; his days fleeing away, and of no more continuance than the shadow cast by the sun, which presently declines and is gone. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(h) \"halitui\", Muis; so Kimchi. (i) \"Vapori\", Cocceius; so the Syriac and Arabic versions. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(h) \"halitui\", Muis; so Kimchi. (i) \"Vapori\", Cocceius; so the Syriac and Arabic versions. ",
